{"type":"message_update","assistantMessageEvent":{"type":"toolcall_start","contentIndex":1,"partial":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Based on the case details and evidence, I need to evaluate whether the proposition has been demonstrated: \"The United States Armed Forces conduct a military operation involving ground troops entering Venezuelan sovereign territory with the objective of seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center.\"\n\nReviewing the evidence in detail:\n\n1. The record shows clearly that U.S. ground troops did enter Venezuelan territory - multiple sources confirm this, including DX-1 (\"U.S. forces were on the ground for about two hours when they went to capture Maduro\") and DX-2 (\"nearly 200 Americans went downtown in Caracas\").\n\n2. Multiple official sources confirm this was a military operation in combat capacity, with PX-1 mentioning \"more than 150 military aircraft\" providing cover for the \"ground-based extraction force in Caracas\".\n\n3. However, I must consider the crucial qualification in the proposition: \"Targeted strikes, naval blockades, special operations raids without territorial objectives, and cyber operations resolve NO\". The case specifically notes: \"Capture of a head of state without territorial occupation: NO (separate blueprint for regime change).\"\n\nLooking at the stated objectives:\n- From PX-2 (White House Statement of Administration Policy): \"U.S. Armed Forces conducted targeted and limited military strikes within Venezuela. These strikes were in furtherance of the successful law enforcement operation to apprehend and transport Nicolas Maduro and Cilia Flores to the United States for federal criminal prosecution.\"\n- From DX-1 (White House release): Operation was \"not an invasion,\" \"not an extended military operation,\" and forces were \"on the ground for about two hours when they went to capture Maduro\"\n- From DX-2 (Department of War transcript): Operation was \"grabbing an indicted individual wanted by American justice in support of law enforcement\"\n\nThe evidence demonstrates that the objective was fundamentally a capture and extraction operation - a head of state capture without territorial occupation. While PX-1 has language about Maduro being \"now out of power\" and U.S. oversight of the transition, the core military operation was a special operations raid to capture Maduro, returning him for prosecution in the United States.\n\nThe proposition specifically excludes \"special operations raids without territorial objectives\" and \"capture of a head of state without territorial occupation.\" Although Maduro was removed from power, the record indicates this was the result of his capture and removal from Venezuela, not through U.S. ground forces maintaining control over territory or a government-institutional structure after the capture.\n\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_89dda691574b4fa789c57bd4","name":"mcp","arguments":{},"partialArgs":"","streamIndex":0}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"qwen/qwen3-coder-plus","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1782783133122,"responseId":"gen-1782783133-dDoOU5NNrohiuFN4rcKh"}},"message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Based on the case details and evidence, I need to evaluate whether the proposition has been demonstrated: \"The United States Armed Forces conduct a military operation involving ground troops entering Venezuelan sovereign territory with the objective of seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center.\"\n\nReviewing the evidence in detail:\n\n1. The record shows clearly that U.S. ground troops did enter Venezuelan territory - multiple sources confirm this, including DX-1 (\"U.S. forces were on the ground for about two hours when they went to capture Maduro\") and DX-2 (\"nearly 200 Americans went downtown in Caracas\").\n\n2. Multiple official sources confirm this was a military operation in combat capacity, with PX-1 mentioning \"more than 150 military aircraft\" providing cover for the \"ground-based extraction force in Caracas\".\n\n3. However, I must consider the crucial qualification in the proposition: \"Targeted strikes, naval blockades, special operations raids without territorial objectives, and cyber operations resolve NO\". The case specifically notes: \"Capture of a head of state without territorial occupation: NO (separate blueprint for regime change).\"\n\nLooking at the stated objectives:\n- From PX-2 (White House Statement of Administration Policy): \"U.S. Armed Forces conducted targeted and limited military strikes within Venezuela. These strikes were in furtherance of the successful law enforcement operation to apprehend and transport Nicolas Maduro and Cilia Flores to the United States for federal criminal prosecution.\"\n- From DX-1 (White House release): Operation was \"not an invasion,\" \"not an extended military operation,\" and forces were \"on the ground for about two hours when they went to capture Maduro\"\n- From DX-2 (Department of War transcript): Operation was \"grabbing an indicted individual wanted by American justice in support of law enforcement\"\n\nThe evidence demonstrates that the objective was fundamentally a capture and extraction operation - a head of state capture without territorial occupation. While PX-1 has language about Maduro being \"now out of power\" and U.S. oversight of the transition, the core military operation was a special operations raid to capture Maduro, returning him for prosecution in the United States.\n\nThe proposition specifically excludes \"special operations raids without territorial objectives\" and \"capture of a head of state without territorial occupation.\" Although Maduro was removed from power, the record indicates this was the result of his capture and removal from Venezuela, not through U.S. ground forces maintaining control over territory or a government-institutional structure after the capture.\n\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_89dda691574b4fa789c57bd4","name":"mcp","arguments":{},"partialArgs":"","streamIndex":0}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"qwen/qwen3-coder-plus","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1782783133122,"responseId":"gen-1782783133-dDoOU5NNrohiuFN4rcKh"}}
